-- Sub-Saharan African Stocks Report: First Bank, Gamma Civic, Oando Active
-- B y   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a
-- 2010-09-29T12:06:55Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-29/sub-saharan-african-stocks-report-first-bank-gamma-civic-oando-active.html
The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index  surged the most since March, rising 3.2 percent to
23,142.95 as of 12:20 p.m. in Lagos.  Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  increased for a second day,
gaining less than 0.1 percent to close at 1,774.36 by 1:30 p.m.
in Port Louis. Kenya’s  All-Share Index  declined for the fourth
time in five days, dropping less than 0.1 percent to 82.78 by
2:15 p.m. in Nairobi. Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index 
increased for a third day, rallying 0.3 percent to 793.78 by
12:27 p.m. in Windhoek, while the  Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share
Index  advanced the most in a month, adding 1.5 percent to
6,754.81 by 11:29 a.m. in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  First Bank of Nigeria Plc  (FIRSTBAN NL), the West African
nation’s largest lender by market value, snapped the longest
streak of losses in 13 months, climbing 21 kobo, or 2 percent,
to 10.91 naira. The bank is considering entering four new
markets in Africa over the next year to meet the needs of
corporate customers, Managing Director  Stephen Olabisi Onasanya 
said. The company will show “some growth” in its loan book by
the fourth quarter, he said in a televised interview with
Johannesburg-based CNBC Africa.  Gamma Civic Ltd.  (GML MP), a Mauritian company with
interests in construction and the country’s lottery, fell the
most in 10 months, slumping 22 rupees, or 8.1 percent, to 250
rupees. Full-year profit dropped 52 percent to 161.3 million
rupees ($5.2 million), the company said in a statement to the
stock exchange today.  Oando Plc  (OANDO NL), Nigeria’s biggest fuel retailer, rose
for the first time in four trading days, gaining 2.76 naira, or
5 percent, to 58.26 naira. The company announced plans to
acquire assets to help it meet an oil-production target of
100,000 barrels per day within three years. To achieve this
target, Oando wants to buy production assets within six months,
Degbola Abudu, head of corporate finance, said at a conference
yesterday in Lagos. Oando currently produces as much as 6,000
barrels per day, he said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
